Separate Analysis and Summary Statistics¶

In [14]:
# Creating separate DataFrames for B2B and B2C

df_b2b = df[df['Customer_Type'] == 'B2B']
df_b2c = df[df['Customer_Type'] == 'B2C']

Reason for Separate Analysis:¶

One of the key objectives is to "Evaluate the impact of discounts on revenue and profit margins for B2B customers."¶

B2B customers often exhibit different purchasing behaviors (e.g., bulk orders, negotiated discounts) compared to B2C customers.¶

Analyzing them separately allows us to isolate the specific impact of discounts on the B2B segment, as required by the objective,¶

and avoid misleading conclusions that might arise from combining both segments. Furthermore, B2B customers are likely the source of the outliers seen in the overall analysis.¶

1. Analyze Revenue and Profitability by Customer Type¶

Objective: Understand the revenue contribution and profitability of B2B vs. B2C customers.¶

In [17]:
# Revenue and Profitability by Customer Type

customer_summary = df.groupby('Customer_Type').agg({
    'Total_Price': 'sum',
    'Discount': 'mean',
    'Quantity': 'sum'
}).reset_index()

customer_summary.rename(columns={
    'Total_Price': 'Total_Revenue',
    'Discount': 'Avg_Discount',
    'Quantity': 'Total_Quantity'
}, inplace=True)

# Visualization
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
sns.barplot(data=customer_summary, x='Customer_Type', y='Total_Revenue', palette='coolwarm')
plt.title('Total Revenue by Customer Type', fontsize=16)
plt.xlabel('Customer Type', fontsize=12)
plt.ylabel('Total Revenue', fontsize=12)
plt.show()

4. Product-Level Profitability Analysis¶

Objective: Identify the most and least profitable products¶

In [20]:
# Profitability by Product
product_summary = df.groupby('Product').agg({
    'Total_Price': 'sum',
    'Quantity': 'sum',
    'Unit_Price': 'mean'
}).reset_index()

product_summary['Revenue_Per_Unit'] = product_summary['Total_Price'] / product_summary['Quantity']

# Visualization
top_products = product_summary.sort_values('Total_Price', ascending=False).head(10)

plt.figure(figsize=(14, 8))
sns.barplot(data=top_products, x='Product', y='Total_Price', color='lightgreen')
plt.title('Top 10 Products by Total Revenue', fontsize=16)
plt.xlabel('Product', fontsize=12)
plt.ylabel('Total Revenue', fontsize=12)
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.show()

5. Trend Analysis (Monthly Sales)¶

Objective: Analyze sales trends over time to identify seasonality or growth patterns¶

In [21]:
# Monthly Sales Analysis
df['Month_Year'] = df['Order_Date'].dt.to_period('M')

# Group and convert 'Month_Year' to string for plotting
monthly_sales = df.groupby('Month_Year').agg({'Total_Price': 'sum'}).reset_index()
monthly_sales['Month_Year'] = monthly_sales['Month_Year'].astype(str)  # Convert to string

# Visualization
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
sns.lineplot(data=monthly_sales, x='Month_Year', y='Total_Price', marker='o', color='coral')
plt.title('Monthly Sales Trend', fontsize=16)
plt.xlabel('Month-Year', fontsize=12)
plt.ylabel('Total Revenue', fontsize=12)
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.grid()
plt.show()

7. Impact of Discounts on Revenue (B2B Only)¶

Objective: Assess how discounts affect revenue in the B2B segment.¶

In [24]:
b2b_discount_impact = df_b2b.groupby('Category').apply(lambda x: pd.Series({
    'Total Revenue': x['Total_Price'].sum(),
    'Revenue Without Discount': (x['Total_Price'] / (1-x['Discount'])).sum(),
    'Discount Amount': ((x['Total_Price'] / (1-x['Discount'])).sum() - x['Total_Price'].sum())
}))
print("\nB2B Discount Impact:\n", b2b_discount_impact)
